In[]:
# Create a win_percentage_category to include high, medium, and low win percentages
football['win_percentage_category'] = pd.qcut(football['win_percentage'], q=3, labels=['low', 'medium', 'high'])

# Create a new gdp_category to include high, medium, high and very high gdp by manually setting the bins
football['gdp_category'] = pd.cut(football['gdp_chained_million_dollar'], bins=[0, 100000, 250000, 400000, np.inf], labels=['low', 'medium', 'high', 'very high'])

# Create a home_attendance_rate_category to include high, medium, and low home attendance
football['home_attendance_rate_category'] = pd.qcut(football['home_attendance_rate_per_game'], q=3, labels=['low', 'medium', 'high'])

# Create a unique id for each team which includes the team name and the year
football['team_id'] = football['team_name'] + '_' + football['year'].astype(str)

Convert playoffs and renovated columns to boolean

In[]:
# convert the playoffs column to boolean
football['playoffs'] = football['playoffs'].apply(lambda x: True if x == 'Playoffs' else False)

# convert the renovated column to boolean
football['renovated'] = football['renovated'].apply(lambda x: True if x == 1 else False)

Create Pipelines for Different Data Types

In[]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import RobustScaler, OrdinalEncoder
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
# create a pipeline for the numeric features
numeric_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='median')),
    ('scaler', RobustScaler()) # use RobustScaler to reduce the influence of outliers
])

# create a pipeline for the onehot features
onehot_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')),
    ('encoder', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'))
])

# create a pipeline for the ordinal features
ordinal_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')),
    ('encoder', OrdinalEncoder())
])

# combine the pipelines
full_pipeline = ColumnTransformer([
    ('numeric', numeric_pipeline, numeric_features),
    ('onehot', onehot_pipeline, onehot_features),
    ('ordinal', ordinal_pipeline, ordinal_features)
])

# fit and transform the data
X_prepared = full_pipeline.fit_transform(football_X)

X_prepared = X_prepared.toarray()

Clustering Analysis

Goal

Cluster the teams by related features and find similar patterns of teams with similar home attendance rates, as well as distinguishing the difference between different clusters.

Steps

  • Agglomerative Clustering
  • K-Means Clustering

Agglomerative Clustering

Clustering groups data based on similarity without prior labels (unsupervised).

In[]:

# implement a function to plot the scatterplot with different number of clusters and dimensions
def plot_cluster(dimension, clusters):
    plt.scatter(dimension[:, 0], dimension[:, 1], c=clusters.fit_predict(dimension), alpha=0.6) # plot the first two dimensions
    plt.title(f'{dimension.shape[1]} dimensions + {clusters.n_clusters} clusters')

In[]:
# Remove outliers for win_percentage, gdp, and home_attendance_rate for each cluster for each cluster

features_to_clean = ['win_percentage', 'gdp_chained_million_dollar', 'home_attendance_rate_per_game']

# Get the unique clusters
clusters = football_clustered['cluster'].unique()

# Create a new DataFrame to store the non-outliers
non_outliers_df = pd.DataFrame()

for cluster in clusters:
    cluster_data = football_clustered[football_clustered['cluster'] == cluster]
    cluster_mask = pd.Series(True, index=cluster_data.index)

    for feature in features_to_clean:
        # Calculate Q1, Q3 and IQR for each feature within the current cluster
        Q1 = cluster_data[feature].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = cluster_data[feature].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1

        feature_mask = ((cluster_data[feature] >= (Q1 - 1.5 * IQR)) &
                        (cluster_data[feature] <= (Q3 + 1.5 * IQR))) # Create a mask for the current feature (Applied CHATGPT to help with the code)
        cluster_mask &= feature_mask # Combine the masks for all features

    non_outliers_df = pd.concat([non_outliers_df, cluster_data[cluster_mask]], axis=0) # Append the non-outliers to the new DataFrame

football_clustered = non_outliers_df

Agglomerative clustering conclusion

After clustering the data with different dimensions and clusters, we finally chose 2 dimensions and 5 clusters to achieve the best effect. There are significant features in each cluster.

  • Cluster 0: This cluster contains the majority of the teams. The teams have outstanding team performance with most playoffs and superbowl experiences and medium GDP values. There are also the most renovated stadiums in this cluster. The home attendance rate of those teams is the highest among the clusters. We can infer that the high home attendance was a result of the team's performance.

  • Cluster 1: Only a few teams are grouped into this cluster, which have high GDP values and a medium win percentage. The teams in this cluster have the second highest home attendance rate among the five clusters, a testament to their economic prosperity.

  • Cluster 2: The cluster has the lowest win percentage with nearly no playoff experience. The GDP values of the teams also range from medium to low. As a result, the home attendance rate in this cluster is the lowest.

  • Cluster 3: This cluster has the second most teams attributed to it, with a medium win percentage but the lowest gdp values. The teams have had some playoff and even superbowl experiences. The home attendance rate of the cluster is higher than that of cluster 2. It can be inferred that good team performance can improve home attendance to some extent, even though the team is located in a low-gdp area.

  • Cluster 4: Only five teams, the Los Angeles Chargers from 2017 to 2018 and the Los Angeles Rams from 2016 to 2018, belong to this cluster, which can be considered outliers. The teams have extremely high GDP values, and their performance is also good. However, the home attendance rate is the second-lowest among the five clusters. This may be due to the stadium's large capacity and the team's location adjustments.

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn import metrics

# calculate the silhouette scores for different clusters and dimensions
silhouette_scores = []
dimensions = [X_pca_2, X_pca_3, X_pca_4, X_pca_5]
for i in range(4):
    for j in range(2, 7):
        kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=j, random_state=0, n_init=10)
        cluster_labels = kmeans.fit_predict(dimensions[i])
        silhouette_scores.append(f"dimension{i+2}_cluster{j}: {metrics.silhouette_score(dimensions[i], cluster_labels):.2f}")

In[]:
# create a DataFrame for the two principal components
principalDf = pd.DataFrame(data = X_pca_2, columns = ['principal component 1', 'principal component 2'])

# visualize the silhouette scores and the performance of the cluster
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_samples, silhouette_score
import matplotlib.cm as cm # colormaps

X = principalDf.values
y = football_y

range_n_clusters = [3]
# Code is referenced from the in-class notebook
for n_clusters in range_n_clusters:
    # Create a subplot with 1 row and 2 columns
    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2)
    fig.set_size_inches(18, 7)

    # The 1st subplot is the silhouette plot
    # The silhouette coefficient can range from -1, 1 but in this example all
    # lie within [-0.1, 1]
    ax1.set_xlim([-0.1, 1])
    # The (n_clusters+1)*10 is for inserting blank space between silhouette
    # plots of individual clusters, to demarcate them clearly.
    ax1.set_ylim([0, len(X) + (n_clusters + 1) * 10])

    # Initialize the clusterer with n_clusters value and a random generator
    # seed of 42 for reproducibility.
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters, n_init="auto", random_state=42)
    cluster_labels = clusterer.fit_predict(X)

    # The silhouette_score gives the average value for all the samples.
    # This gives a perspective into the density and separation of the formed
    # clusters
    silhouette_avg = silhouette_score(X, cluster_labels)
    print("For n_clusters =", n_clusters,
        "The average silhouette_score is :", silhouette_avg)

    # Compute the silhouette scores for each sample
    sample_silhouette_values = silhouette_samples(X, cluster_labels)

    y_lower = 10
    for i in range(n_clusters):
        # Aggregate the silhouette scores for samples belonging to
        # cluster i, and sort them
        ith_cluster_silhouette_values = sample_silhouette_values[cluster_labels == i]

        ith_cluster_silhouette_values.sort()

        size_cluster_i = ith_cluster_silhouette_values.shape[0]
        y_upper = y_lower + size_cluster_i

        color = cm.nipy_spectral(float(i) / n_clusters)
        ax1.fill_betweenx(np.arange(y_lower, y_upper),
                        0, ith_cluster_silhouette_values,
                        facecolor=color, edgecolor=color, alpha=0.7)

        # Label the silhouette plots with their cluster numbers at the middle
        ax1.text(-0.05, y_lower + 0.5 * size_cluster_i, str(i))

        # Compute the new y_lower for next plot
        y_lower = y_upper + 10  # 10 for the 0 samples

    ax1.set_title("The silhouette plot for the various clusters.")
    ax1.set_xlabel("The silhouette coefficient values")
    ax1.set_ylabel("Cluster label")

    # The vertical line for average silhouette score of all the values
    ax1.axvline(x=silhouette_avg, color="red", linestyle="--")

    ax1.set_yticks([])  # Clear the yaxis labels / ticks
    ax1.set_xticks([-0.1, 0, 0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1])

    # 2nd Plot showing the actual clusters formed
    colors = cm.nipy_spectral(cluster_labels.astype(float) / n_clusters)
    ax2.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], marker='.', s=30, lw=0, alpha=0.7,
                c=colors, edgecolor='k')

    # Labeling the clusters
    centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_
    # Draw white circles at cluster centers
    ax2.scatter(centers[:, 0], centers[:, 1], marker='o',
                c="white", alpha=1, s=200, edgecolor='k')

    for i, c in enumerate(centers):
        ax2.scatter(c[0], c[1], marker='$%d$' % i, alpha=1,
                    s=50, edgecolor='k')

    ax2.set_title("The visualization of the clustered data.")
    ax2.set_xlabel("Feature space for the 1st feature")
    ax2.set_ylabel("Feature space for the 2nd feature")

    plt.suptitle(("Silhouette analysis for KMeans clustering on sample data "
                  "with n_clusters = %d" % n_clusters),
                 fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')

plt.show()

For n_clusters = 3 The average silhouette_score is : 0.42429880285322663

There are no clusters below the average silhouette score. There is nearly no overlap between different clusters, and the intra-cluster distance is very small.

# Remove outliers for win_percentage, gdp, and home_attendance_rate for each cluster for each cluster

for cluster in cluster_kmeans_data['cluster'].unique():
    cluster_data = cluster_kmeans_data[cluster_kmeans_data['cluster'] == cluster]
    cluster_mask = pd.Series(True, index=cluster_data.index)

    for feature in features_to_clean:
        # Calculate Q1, Q3 and IQR for each feature within the current cluster
        Q1 = cluster_data[feature].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = cluster_data[feature].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1

        feature_mask = ((cluster_data[feature] >= (Q1 - 1.5 * IQR)) &
                        (cluster_data[feature] <= (Q3 + 1.5 * IQR))) # Create a mask for the current feature
        cluster_mask &= feature_mask # Combine the masks for all features

    non_outliers_df = pd.concat([non_outliers_df, cluster_data[cluster_mask]], axis=0) # Append the non-outliers to the new DataFrame
    cluster_kmeans_data = non_outliers_df

# This corrects majority of the outliers in the data

K-Means Clustering Analysis

By checking the silhouette scores of different dimensions and clusters, we chose 2 dimensions and 3 clusters for the K-means clustering. There are also significant features for each cluster.

  • Cluster 0: 27% of the teams are grouped into this cluster. The teams in this cluster have the worst team performance and very low gdp values, which leads to the lowest home attendance rate. These teams also have the fewest playoff and superbowl experiences.

  • Cluster 1: The cluster has the fewest teams, about 10%. The teams have outstanding team performance and extremely high GDP values. As a result, the home attendance rate in the cluster is the highest.

  • Cluster 2: Most teams are attributed to this cluster, which is more than 62%. The teams also have high win percentages, but their GDP values are the lowest. And there are most teams with playoff experience in this cluster. As a result, the home attendance rate of this cluster is only a little lower than cluster 1. It can be inferred that team performance is a more important influencing feature than local GDP on home attendance rate.

Final Conclusion

According to the Agglomerative Clustering and K-Means Clustering Analysis, the teams are divided into several groups with significant features, which lead to different levels of home attendance rates. Here are the conclusions we can draw.

  • Most teams in the NFL are located in areas with median to low GDP categories, but they have stable team performance and the most playoff experience. The home attendance rate of the teams also maintains a high level. We can infer that team performance significantly influences the home attendance rate.
  • The home attendance remains the lowest when the team performs badly and is also located in a low-GDP area.
  • Only a few teams own both high GDP locations and good team performance. However, the effect of the local economy on home attendance rates is not as significant as team performance.
  • Teams with stadium renovation records only take up a small portion of the sample, which can hardly be considered an influencing factor in the research.
